                                <li><strong>Adjust for your home’s needs:</strong> Older homes usually require higher upkeep costs.</li>
                                <li><strong>Account for inflation:</strong> Plan for increasing material and labor costs over time.</li>
                            </ul>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Set Up a Home Maintenance Fund</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">One of the best ways to budget for home repairs is by setting up a dedicated home maintenance fund. This fund should be separate from your regular savings or emergency fund.</p>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Prioritize Repairs and Maintenance Tasks</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Not all home maintenance tasks are equally urgent. Focus on structural and safety issues first, such as roof leaks or faulty wiring, before moving on to cosmetic upgrades like painting.</p>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Track Past Maintenance Expenses</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Keep a detailed log of all repairs, including the cost and nature of the work. Analyzing these trends helps you predict future costs more accurately.</p>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Plan for Seasonal Maintenance</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Many tasks are seasonal. Whether it’s cleaning gutters in the fall or servicing the HVAC in summer, budgeting for these ahead of time prevents last-minute financial strain.</p>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Factor in Home Improvement Projects</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Identify value-adding projects like kitchen or bathroom upgrades. Always add a 10-20% contingency amount to your project estimates to cover unexpected overages.</p>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Hire Professionals vs. DIY</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">While DIY can save money on simple tasks like painting, complex electrical or plumbing issues are best handled by licensed professionals to ensure safety and quality.</p>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Regularly Inspect Your Home</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Catching small issues early is the key to low-cost maintenance. Schedule regular checks on critical systems like your roof and plumbing to spot wear and tear promptly.</p>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Review Your Home Insurance Coverage</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Review your policy annually. While insurance covers major disasters, remember that routine maintenance is almost always the homeowner's financial responsibility.</p>
    
                            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Set a Contingency Fund for Unexpected Repairs</h2>
                            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4">Allocate 10-15% of your maintenance budget specifically for emergencies like a broken furnace or major leak. Keep this fund in a liquid savings account for easy access.</p>
    
